Make your code available. If you have to develop a software for your data analysis, it is always a good idea to publish your code. The git versioning system offers both a way to release your code but offers also a versioning system. You can also use Git to interact with your software users. Be sure to specify a license for your code (see the licensing section). Use package and environment management system. By using package and environment management systems like {% tool "conda" %} and its bioinformatics specialized channel {% tool "bioconda" %}, researchers that have got access to your code will be able to easily install specific versions of tools, even older ones, in an isolated environment. They will be able to compile/run your code in an equivalent computational environment, including any dependencies such as the correct version of R or particular libraries and command-line tools your code use. You can also share and preserve your setup by specifying in a environment file which tools you installed.
